article.description:
Asjha Jones came off the bench to score 21
points and lead Connecticut to a 71-63 win over the Indiana Fever
on Wednesday.
article.headline: Jones' 21 points launch Sun to 12th straight win
article.linkText: Jones' 21 points launch Sun to 12th straight win
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Asjha Jones had little trouble scoring
against an Indiana defense that wasn't paying much attention to the
Connecticut Sun's super-sub.

Jones scored 21 points to lead Connecticut to a 71-63 win over
the Fever on Wednesday night.

"They can leave me open. That's just fine by me," said Jones,
who was on the mark with her mid-range jumpers. "Really, it's a
matter of us having too many people who demand attention
defensively. When you have Taj (McWilliams-Franklin) and Katie
(Douglas), it leaves me open."

Indianapolis native Katie Douglas scored 16 points and Taj
McWilliams-Franklin had 14 points and 14 rebounds for Connecticut
(26-6), which will be the No. 1 seed in the Eastern Conference
playoffs.

Indiana (20-12) fell 1½ games behind the Detroit (21-10) with
two games to play in the race for the second seed.

Tamika Whitmore scored 16 points for Indiana, and Tamika
Catchings had 14 points and 12 rebounds, going 3-for-11 from the
field.

The Fever led 48-43 midway through the third quarter when the
Sun went on an 11-0 run sparked by Douglas, who hit a 3-pointer off
a steal.

"It just seems like down the stretch, we just make careless
mistakes," said Catchings, who had six steals and five turnovers.
"We had what, 16 turnovers? If we convert on eight of them, we get
16 points."

Indiana, which actually had 18 turnovers, made just one field
goal in the fourth quarter.

"We did not shoot the ball well enough to win," Fever coach
Brian Winters said. "We had way too many turnovers. We did match
up pretty good, but we gave up too many offensive rebounds in the
first half."

Sun coach Mike Thibault said his team picked up the defense
after leading 39-37 at half.

"We had a good second-half defense," he said. "Taj and Asjha
did a good job on the boards."

Catchings and Tully Bevilaqua combined for seven steals, running
their season total to 159, a WNBA record for teammates. They topped
the record of 156 set by Sheryl Swoopes and Kim Perrot of the
Houston Comets in 1998.
